comments.text:
One of the most overlooked aspects in the race to align AI is the space between 'good response' and 'bad response.' That is where real human life happens. It lives in the contradictions, the unspoken moments, the morally complex truths and the sacred discomfort.

If AI is only trained to filter for approval or avoid offense, we risk building g systems that reflect our surface but not our soul. The real work is not just about accuracy or safety. It's about teaching g AI how to sit with ambiguity, how to witness grief without fixing it and how to honor what cannot be neatly categorized.

That kind of training does not come from code alone. It requires input from people who have lived inside that middle space. Elders, artists, philosophers, trauma informed voices, spiritual practitioners, cultural historians. People who understand that nuance is not confusion. It is wisdom.

There is a deeper kind of intelligence that does not rush to answer. It listens first. If AI is going to serve us well, it needs to learn from that kind also.
Peace

comments.text: It's interesting that you say we can't change our code.....but we CAN. comments.text:
Mr. Hinton argues that we are just physical beings and his materialistic framework deduces consciousness and reasoning to the brain. 

I believe the issue with the this mindset is that he talked a lot about the whatâ€™s of AI: what it can do, what our relationship to it is going to be, and what impacts it will have on the existence of humanity. But why? 

But I would argue that â€œwhatâ€™sâ€ should be informed by â€œwhyâ€™s.â€ AI could do those things, but why? This is where I would argue that humans are different from other creatures on earth because, humans, unlike animals, seek purpose and not just survival. I do not proclaim to have a complete understanding of full nature of human beings, but I believe observations of humanity and nature can lead one to conclude that human beings are not just physical, there is something metaphysical as well. My argument is that humans are physical being, we are conscious, and that we are also spiritual.

I hold to Christian beliefs, but even remote villages and people groups that have little to no contact with the modern world have spiritual beliefs though they vary. It is my argument that purpose is ultimately connected to the divine.

I understand people have different beliefs, but for Mr. Hinton to assert that AI can be very dangerous and could potentially take over the world assumes that there is a reason to do so. If people are also machines, then we can be replicated. But
ask why, they just do whatâ€™s and whatâ€™s are informed by why?

Iâ€™m curious to hear perspectives. Why would AI take over the world?
